# Threat Modelling - PaymentPlatform-SaaS-API-Integration
## Application Info
The payment platform microservice posts a payment request to the SaaS API to process payments and receives a confirmation notification on its queue once successful.

## Assumptions


| Assumption Number | Assumption | Linked Threats | Linked Mitigations | Comments |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| <a name="A-0004"></a>A-0004 | The external API is a multi-tenant API i.e. caters to many customers. | [**T-0008**](#T-0008): A threat actor who can intercept traffic destined to the SaaS API can read payment data, which leads to financial loss and sensitive information disclosure, resulting in reduced confidentiality |  |  |
| <a name="A-0003"></a>A-0003 | Since its a SaaS application, not much of the internals are known | [**T-0010**](#T-0010): A threat actor who can spoof notification service can flood the queue with messages, which leads to no availability for legitimate messages, negatively impacting the payment confirmation process<br/>[**T-0007**](#T-0007): An external threat actor with access to SaaS API can launch denial of service attack, which leads to service being not available to legitimate users, resulting in reduced availability of the SaaS payment platform.<br/>[**T-0013**](#T-0013): ...SaaS API claims that it did not receive data from microservice on the other side of the trust boundary.... |  |  |
| <a name="A-0002"></a>A-0002 | The admin user is already authenticated on platform account through existing authn\/authz mechanism. | [**T-0015**](#T-0015): An internal actor with the required permissions in the AWS account can modify the queue policy or KMS policy or related configuration, which leads to lack of knowledge\/proof of who took the action<br/>[**T-0006**](#T-0006): An internal actor with the required permissions in the AWS account can elevate permissions on key policy, which leads to key being available openly to threat actors, open to misuse<br/>[**T-0005**](#T-0005): An internal actor with the required permissions in the AWS account can restrict permissions on key policy, which leads to denial of access to key which in turn would stop legitimate notification service from writing message in the queue, resulting in reduced integrity and\/or availability of the payment confirmation process<br/>[**T-0004**](#T-0004): An internal actor with the required permissions in the AWS account can restrict permissions on queue policy, which leads to denying access to legitimate notification service, resulting in reduced integrity and\/or availability of the payment process<br/>[**T-0003**](#T-0003): An internal actor with the required permissions in the AWS account can elevate the permissions on queue policy, which leads to queue being available publicly, open to misuse, resulting in reduced integrity and\/or availability |  |  |
| <a name="A-0001"></a>A-0001 | The message from queue is not read by a human or a process as it is not mentioned in the diagram. |  |  |  |

| <a name="T-0017"></a>T-0017 | ...Is personal data stored and retained on SaaS app, as per compliance laws?... | [**M-0016**](#M-0016): Ensure compliance to regulations such as GDPR, PCI-DSS, GLBA etc. as applicable to avoid fines. |  |  Identified | High | I | <p>COMPLIANCE RISK</p> |
| <a name="T-0016"></a>T-0016 | ...In case of cross-region or cross-border payment information submitted to API, are we sure we are compliant with applicable regulation rules like GDPR, PCI-DSS?... | [**M-0016**](#M-0016): Ensure compliance to regulations such as GDPR, PCI-DSS, GLBA etc. as applicable to avoid fines. |  |  Identified | High | I | <p>COMPLIANCE RISK</p> |
| <a name="T-0015"></a>T-0015 | An internal actor with the required permissions in the AWS account can modify the queue policy or KMS policy or related configuration, which leads to lack of knowledge\/proof of who took the action | [**M-0015**](#M-0015): Enable appropriate logging to support non-repudiation - application logs, request\/response logs etc.<br/>[**M-0001**](#M-0001): Enable appropriate CloudTrail logging to capture write events. | [**A-0002**](#A-0002): The admin user is already authenticated on platform account through existing authn\/authz mechanism. |  Identified | High | R, E |  |
| <a name="T-0014"></a>T-0014 | ...Message Queue claims that it did not write data received from an entity on the other side of the trust boundary.... | [**M-0001**](#M-0001): Enable appropriate CloudTrail logging to capture write events.<br/>[**M-0015**](#M-0015): Enable appropriate logging to support non-repudiation - application logs, request\/response logs etc. |  |  Identified | High | R |  |
| <a name="T-0013"></a>T-0013 | ...SaaS API claims that it did not receive data from microservice on the other side of the trust boundary.... | [**M-0001**](#M-0001): Enable appropriate CloudTrail logging to capture write events.<br/>[**M-0015**](#M-0015): Enable appropriate logging to support non-repudiation - application logs, request\/response logs etc. | [**A-0003**](#A-0003): Since its a SaaS application, not much of the internals are known |  Identified | High | R |  |
| <a name="T-0012"></a>T-0012 | An internal actor with the required permissions in the AWS account can modify the VPC egress route towards SaaS payment API, which leads to microservice not being able to access the API, negatively impacting the payment process | [**M-0002**](#M-0002): Implement least privilege access to internal users - attach permission boundaries, SCPs and restrict excessive actions like s3:\*, kms:\* etc. |  |  Identified | High | T, E |  |
| <a name="T-0011"></a>T-0011 | A threat actor with the required permissions in the AWS account can modify the external id in the trust policy to his own, which leads to loss of legitimate access to notification service, negatively impacting the payment confirmation process | [**M-0002**](#M-0002): Implement least privilege access to internal users - attach permission boundaries, SCPs and restrict excessive actions like s3:\*, kms:\* etc.<br/>[**M-0014**](#M-0014): Enable appropriate logging to detect anomalous changes and trigger auto-remediation. |  |  Identified | High | T, D, E |  |
| <a name="T-0010"></a>T-0010 | A threat actor who can spoof notification service can flood the queue with messages, which leads to no availability for legitimate messages, negatively impacting the payment confirmation process | [**M-0013**](#M-0013): DLQs must be put in place to contain malicious activity.<br/>[**M-0012**](#M-0012): Right authentication controls should be put in place on the notification service \(responsibility of the SaaS application\) | [**A-0003**](#A-0003): Since its a SaaS application, not much of the internals are known |  Identified | High | S, D |  |
| <a name="T-0009"></a>T-0009 | An external threat actor who can intercept the message destined towards queue can modify or tamper with the message, which leads to message being unreadable or corrupted, resulting in reduced integrity of the payment confirmation process | [**M-0004**](#M-0004): Enable HTTPS communication in transit.<br/>[**M-0011**](#M-0011): Add signatures to message to verify authenticity.<br/>[**M-0013**](#M-0013): DLQs must be put in place to contain malicious activity. |  |  Identified | Medium | T, I |  |
| <a name="T-0008"></a>T-0008 | A threat actor who can intercept traffic destined to the SaaS API can read payment data, which leads to financial loss and sensitive information disclosure, resulting in reduced confidentiality | [**M-0004**](#M-0004): Enable HTTPS communication in transit.<br/>[**M-0010**](#M-0010): Use strong TLS encryption and add application encryption if necessary. | [**A-0004**](#A-0004): The external API is a multi-tenant API i.e. caters to many customers. |  Identified | Medium | I, T |  |
| <a name="T-0007"></a>T-0007 | An external threat actor with access to SaaS API can launch denial of service attack, which leads to service being not available to legitimate users, resulting in reduced availability of the SaaS payment platform. | [**M-0008**](#M-0008): Ensure adaptive throttling is available to protect from unusual spikes.<br/>[**M-0009**](#M-0009): DDoS protection services are enabled on the API.<br/>[**M-0017**](#M-0017): Maintain SLAs of SaaS API through contractual agreements. | [**A-0003**](#A-0003): Since its a SaaS application, not much of the internals are known |  Identified | High | D |  |
| <a name="T-0006"></a>T-0006 | An internal actor with the required permissions in the AWS account can elevate permissions on key policy, which leads to key being available openly to threat actors, open to misuse | [**M-0007**](#M-0007): Apply KMS CMK key policies to restrict access, whitelist resources that can access the key.<br/>[**M-0002**](#M-0002): Implement least privilege access to internal users - attach permission boundaries, SCPs and restrict excessive actions like s3:\*, kms:\* etc. | [**A-0002**](#A-0002): The admin user is already authenticated on platform account through existing authn\/authz mechanism. |  Identified | High | T, E |  |
| <a name="T-0005"></a>T-0005 | An internal actor with the required permissions in the AWS account can restrict permissions on key policy, which leads to denial of access to key which in turn would stop legitimate notification service from writing message in the queue, resulting in reduced integrity and\/or availability of the payment confirmation process | [**M-0002**](#M-0002): Implement least privilege access to internal users - attach permission boundaries, SCPs and restrict excessive actions like s3:\*, kms:\* etc.<br/>[**M-0007**](#M-0007): Apply KMS CMK key policies to restrict access, whitelist resources that can access the key. | [**A-0002**](#A-0002): The admin user is already authenticated on platform account through existing authn\/authz mechanism. |  Identified | High | T, D, E |  |
| <a name="T-0004"></a>T-0004 | An internal actor with the required permissions in the AWS account can restrict permissions on queue policy, which leads to denying access to legitimate notification service, resulting in reduced integrity and\/or availability of the payment process | [**M-0005**](#M-0005): Configure queue policy on the queue whitelisting specific sources to deliver messages and specific sources to configure\/amend the queue.<br/>[**M-0002**](#M-0002): Implement least privilege access to internal users - attach permission boundaries, SCPs and restrict excessive actions like s3:\*, kms:\* etc. | [**A-0002**](#A-0002): The admin user is already authenticated on platform account through existing authn\/authz mechanism. |  Identified | High | D, E, T |  |
| <a name="T-0003"></a>T-0003 | An internal actor with the required permissions in the AWS account can elevate the permissions on queue policy, which leads to queue being available publicly, open to misuse, resulting in reduced integrity and\/or availability | [**M-0002**](#M-0002): Implement least privilege access to internal users - attach permission boundaries, SCPs and restrict excessive actions like s3:\*, kms:\* etc.<br/>[**M-0005**](#M-0005): Configure queue policy on the queue whitelisting specific sources to deliver messages and specific sources to configure\/amend the queue. | [**A-0002**](#A-0002): The admin user is already authenticated on platform account through existing authn\/authz mechanism. |  Identified | High | D, E, T |  |
| <a name="T-0002"></a>T-0002 | A threat actor with the required permissions in the AWS account can spoof the message queue with his own queue, which leads to messages being delivered to wrong queue, resulting in reduced authenticity of the payment confirmation process | [**M-0006**](#M-0006): Create consumer roles with least privilege access and grant specific access on queue, and whitelist the specific role through queue policy. |  |  Identified | Low | S, I |  |
| <a name="T-0001"></a>T-0001 | A threat actor who is able to spoof the SaaS external API can access and read sensitive PCI data, which leads to disclosure of sensitive data and potential compliance fines, negatively impacting the SaaS payment platform. | [**M-0003**](#M-0003): Enable authentication and authorisation on API for each customer\/tenant. |  |  Identified | High | S, I |  |

## Impacted Assets


| Assets Number | Asset | Related Threats |
| --- | --- | --- |
| AS-0001 | the payment process | [**T-0012**](#T-0012): An internal actor with the required permissions in the AWS account can modify the VPC egress route towards SaaS payment API, which leads to microservice not being able to access the API, negatively impacting the payment process<br/>[**T-0004**](#T-0004): An internal actor with the required permissions in the AWS account can restrict permissions on queue policy, which leads to denying access to legitimate notification service, resulting in reduced integrity and\/or availability of the payment process |
| AS-0002 | the payment confirmation process | [**T-0011**](#T-0011): A threat actor with the required permissions in the AWS account can modify the external id in the trust policy to his own, which leads to loss of legitimate access to notification service, negatively impacting the payment confirmation process<br/>[**T-0010**](#T-0010): A threat actor who can spoof notification service can flood the queue with messages, which leads to no availability for legitimate messages, negatively impacting the payment confirmation process<br/>[**T-0009**](#T-0009): An external threat actor who can intercept the message destined towards queue can modify or tamper with the message, which leads to message being unreadable or corrupted, resulting in reduced integrity of the payment confirmation process<br/>[**T-0005**](#T-0005): An internal actor with the required permissions in the AWS account can restrict permissions on key policy, which leads to denial of access to key which in turn would stop legitimate notification service from writing message in the queue, resulting in reduced integrity and\/or availability of the payment confirmation process<br/>[**T-0002**](#T-0002): A threat actor with the required permissions in the AWS account can spoof the message queue with his own queue, which leads to messages being delivered to wrong queue, resulting in reduced authenticity of the payment confirmation process |
| AS-0003 | the SaaS payment platform. | [**T-0007**](#T-0007): An external threat actor with access to SaaS API can launch denial of service attack, which leads to service being not available to legitimate users, resulting in reduced availability of the SaaS payment platform.<br/>[**T-0001**](#T-0001): A threat actor who is able to spoof the SaaS external API can access and read sensitive PCI data, which leads to disclosure of sensitive data and potential compliance fines, negatively impacting the SaaS payment platform. |
